76561197968878135,Recommended,215630,9612571,"Posted: 23 March, 2014",all,Chris,"Interesting enough RPG; very similar to the first Dragon Age.VERY complicated skill system; points are earned from defeating enemies, completing quests or solving skill challenges.  Using magic during fights converts some of the earned points in to ""gift points"" that can be exclusively spent upgrading magic abilities. The remainder of points can be spent on combat special abilities, skills (up to rank 5 of 7), stats that improve 2 skills, or stats that effect your combat capabilities.  Investing in skills early is a sure way to earn ongoing dividends throughout the game.Story was... interesting.  Well crafted universe with plenty of detailed back story, however the game does expect that you the player will memorize it.  Just learned a complex, multi-sentence incantation? Better hope you remember it precisely when it comes time to enter it because the game provides no ""your character knows this, so click here for the correct option"" which is a bit jarring given the ""follow the blinking quest marker to the hidden clues"" hand-holding presented at various points.Largest complaint: No manual saves. I understand that this is intended to actually invest you in the choices you makein the context of the Role Playing aspect by removing the ability to trivially alter your choices, but it can also be somewhat obnoxious when exploring large areas to have to find the next thing that triggers a save point.  Luckily the game saves after every fight and provides enough 3-6 minion skirmishes at various points that you're never terribly far away from a save point."
