76561198007073556,Recommended,215630,9624313,"Posted: 24 March, 2014",all,EddyDecapitated,"I've seen a fair amount of negativity surrounding Demonicon since its release - which is what has kept me away from the game until a recent sale. Having just beaten the game this morning, I feel very comfortable recommending this game to RPG fans, or anyone looking for a unique and enjoyable story.Demonicon's strengths lie in its commendable use of The Dark Eye universe, it's RPG & skill systems, the creative and thoroughly engaging story line, the focus on narrative and characters, and a well implemented choice system that affects the story and game world.The Dark Eye ruleset may not be represented to the degree that you see in Drakensang, but Demonicon's skills, spells and combat abilities are very well implemented. Its a joy to play a game that puts such high focus on character skills, such as Perception, Fast Talk, Lock Picking, etc. I highly recommend focusing on skills and spells (and less so on combat abilities) if you play the game. I also do recommend playing the game on Hard, as it is quite easy.Cairon's tale may not come across as truly unique in the first half of the game, but those who play all the way through to the end will enjoy a well paced and fairly well written tale that delves into Barboradianism. I've played a lot of RPGs, and I will always remember Demonicon's story - it is the game's standout feature. I really don't want to touch on the story line much, as I feel it is best for the player to delve into it with as few preconceived notions as possible. Suffice it to say that the plot synopsises and game descriptions do not give it justice.Demonicon places a lot of focus on character interaction and player choice. You will spend a siginificant amount of time in conversations with other characters, and in several points throughout the game what you say and decide will affect the game world, the characters and the story. The interplay of the strong, unusual story with the choice system that allows the player to shape how it develops and ends is quite gripping.Cairon may come across as a stale lead with poor attitude, but he develops well across the story, and I ended up being quite fond of him by the end of the game. He also has the distinction (late game) of wearing what is easily one of the coolest sets of armor I have ever seen. I was constantly taking screenshots of Cairon in his end game gear - it is exceedingly creative and morbid.Another factor that helps to amplify the impact and appeal of Demonicon's tale is the well realized game world. The graphics may be dated, but the locations throughout the game are distinctively bleak. Demonicon possesses its own imaginative, sepulchral take on The Dark Eye universe that extends from impressive locations, atmosphere, mood and detail to outright kooky and disturbing events and supporting characters. There is a heavy fixation on the undead, necromancy, demons, suffering, plague, prostitution, and damnation - and I believe it was handled in a way that elevated Demonicon into something quite unique among RPGS.I believe you play Demonicon for the kooky and imaginatively morbid storyline, the immersive game world, and the well designed choice & rpg systems. These are all wrapped up in dated graphics and sloppy combat - but I find most old school rpg players are quite accustomed to that by now;  the graphics and gameplay fit like an old shirt that brings back memories."
