,Recommended,215630,11148387,"Posted: 9 July, 2014",all,Aqua,"It's very clear that this game was following in the footsteps of giants, it's most definitely trying to be Dragon Age: Origins, however it is not. The combat is very clunky, the skill system is un-imaginatve and very VERY limited and the stats are not very well thought out. They opted to have 2 seperate stat trees one for combat and one for immersion/crafting, while I think it's nice there is almost 0 reason to even touch the combat stats(str,agi, etc...). The combat early on makes you want to put points in stats to take more hits, but once you unlock the skill tree of your choice there isn't a point, I had maxed out all of the talents like haggle (merchant prices) and perception (seeing traps and treasure) before I had more than a few points in some early combat stats. However with all that game isn't really all that bad, the story is interesting enough and many of the choices you make force you to think for a moment about what you are doing, which is refreshing.                                                      Truly the biggest issues I had with this game were clucky combat, limited skills, worthless stats and how every area was so isolated, it didn't need to be open world but the overall content of the game was smaller than most, oh and that every weapon upgrade came from vendors, only ever used one weapon I found that wasn't from a vendor, which kinda spoils the immersion factor since this is an RPG. But I'd still say this game is overall not bad, not great, but not bad. Worth it when it's on sale for $10 or so. Personally I'd like to see this developer try their hand at another RPG, but one that is longer and better thought out.Overall I'd give it a 6/10."
